SIMPLE: sanctity
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sanctity
<hw>Sanc"ti*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Sanctities</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. <ets>sanctitas</ets>,
from <ets>sanctus</ets> holy. See <er>Saint</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The state or quality of being sacred or holy; holiness;
saintliness; moral purity; godliness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>sanctity</qex> she made no pretense, and, indeed, narrowly
escaped the imputation of irreligion.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Sacredness; solemnity; inviolability; religious
binding force; <as>as, the <ex>sanctity</ex> of an oath</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A saint or holy being.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>About him all the <qex>sanctities</qex> of heaven.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Holiness; godliness; piety; devotion; goodness;
purity; religiousness; sacredness; solemnity. See the Note under
<er>Religion</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sanctuarize</ent>⟦br⟧
